metadata.name: Geode #45
metadata.description:
A single seed shape is chosen from 13, and placed onto the plane. At every step, a copy of this seed is laid edge-to-edge adjacent to an existing shape, without causing any overlaps. This copy is colored based on the edge it shares with the existing shape. The process continues until the animation completes.

New shapes are placed closest to a moving target. In some mints, this target is slow moving, causing new shapes to expand radially from the seed. In other mints, this target races around, causing new shapes to chase it. 

Each of the 13 shapes forms different patterns under different circumstances. Not all patterns will be explored.

Controls:
  - SPACE: Pause/unpause the animation.
  - ENTER: Skip the animation.
  - R: Restart the animation.

URL Params:
  - "preview=1": Skip the animation.
  - "flex=1": Adapt the boundaries to the size of the window.
  - “slow=1”: Draw only one shape per frame.

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: Multidimensional Maximalism #111
metadata.description:
Multidimensional Maximalism is my learning experience with layering and composition.

Using the Cellular Automaton algorithm from "Gen., Machina" we create multiple dimensions of life. Each with it's own unique evolution and structure. Like petri dishes in a lab. We then use different compositional elements to explore these dimensions.

100% code - as always.

Available overlays
--
* Lasers (drawing inspiration from The Harvest by Per Kristian Stoveland)
* Circleblend
* Drops
* Lenses
* Squares
* Crazysquares
* Waves
* Tesseract (drawing inspiration from the awesome Tesseract collection by Studio Yorktown)
* None (unlucky you)

Controls (in live view):
--
Press [1-9] to set the export scale ratio
Press [s] to save a high resolution image [ resolution x scale ]

enjoy.

metadata.name: Shape Study  #86
metadata.description:
“Everyone has their own shape.”
We meet shapes of all kinds in our life.

Algorithmic randomness generates shapes ever so slightly different yet similar. 
I suppose these are someone’s collection.

“Why do they need to have so many similar things?”

Perhaps it’s their versatility in the pleasure they could bring.
Perhaps they’re meant for different occasions.
Perhaps some are left to search for their very own shapes.

Seeing this, I realized that when people explore themselves or others, it is also a form of shape study.
With what’s visible and concrete, explore the unseen and abstract.

However, good shapes only come by chance.
Shapes, in truth, cannot be good or bad in and of themselves. It’s only when two shapes come together that the meaning thereof arises.
I hope you who decide to pick up this work will find the shapes to your liking.

『每個人都有自己的形狀』
並且每個人一生中也會認識各種形狀

程式的隨機性讓我產生的每個形狀都相似而不同
我想像這也許是某個人的蒐藏
『為什麼會需要擁有這麼多相似的道具呢？』

也許是它們有著不同的功能，能帶來不同的愉悅；
也許是適用於不同的場景
也許是遲遲未找到屬於自己的形狀

想像至此，我意識到：當人們探索自己／他人的同時，也可以說是一種形狀研究
用一個看得見的具體，去探索一個看不見的抽象

然而，好的形狀是可遇不可求的
其實形狀本身沒有好壞，只有當兩個形狀相遇時，形狀才有了意義
希望蒐藏這件作品的各位都可以遇到喜歡的形狀

metadata.name: Paths That Join #44
metadata.description:
Connections, paths, flow. Paths That Join is about representing these ideas in a simple and poignant way. There is an invisible grid. Points are selected at random, serving as anchors, joints to a whole. Like the five pointed star that you could draw with a stroke of a pen without lifting the nib, the selected points are connected and their order is also random. An arc or a straight path connect any two points. The paths they make pulsate, spreading color into the surrounding pixels. Their arrangements criss-cross or, in other iterations, evoke glyphs and abstract park plans. Their directions are both circular and angular. They are paths that join. 

This piece is created with P5.js, p5Fbo by Adam Ferriss and ShadowCLJS for You Topia, an exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art and The NFT Gallery. 

Paths That Join is best viewed in Chrome at a resolution of 1920x1080.

metadata.name: MEGDAZ II #110
metadata.description:
Welcome to Megdaz II - one the most beautiful of all Central High Atlas area of Morocco.

I wanted to create an animated version of Megdaz - subtile movements but still interesting enough to observe the whole scene.

This artwork shows Megdaz as abstract town at different times and places:
- cafe terrace at night
- at the pool
- at the river
- before a mirror
- at the central park
- end of summer
- supper at Emmaus
- at the melting pot
- at the game

The canvas resolution is 4096x4096

--

Generative Art created by Michael Vogt (@neophob).
